        "id": "d6b57545-65f6-4c39-80d5-000200000600",
        "phaseNumber": 6,
        "title": "Closing: Gray Zones and What's Next",
        "estimatedMinutes": 5,
        "sections": [
          {
            "sectionType": "text",
            "content": {
              "markdown": "## The \"Gray Zone\" Recap\n\nYou've classified 14 accounts today. The ones students most often get wrong:\n\n| Account | Common Mistake | Why It's Actually... |\n|---------|---------------|----------------------|\n| Prepaid Insurance | Listed as Liability (\"we paid the insurer, so we owe them\") | **Asset** — we've already paid; the future coverage belongs to us |\n| Deferred Revenue | Listed as Asset (\"we have the cash!\") | **Liability** — we owe the client their service |\n| Owner Drawings | Listed as Expense (\"Sarah spent money\") | **Reduces Equity** — it's not an operating cost; it's the owner reclaiming her stake |\n\nThe trick: don't ask \"did money move in or out?\" Ask \"who has a claim on this?\"\n\n**Reflection prompt:** In your own words, explain why Deferred Revenue is a Liability, not an Asset. What does TechStart owe, and to whom?"
            }
          },
          {
            "sectionType": "text",
            "content": {
              "markdown": "## What's Coming in Lesson 3\n\nYou can now classify accounts. Next, you'll see what happens to those classifications **when business events occur**.\n\nIn **Lesson 3**, TechStart has five new transactions — and for each one, you'll track which category goes up and which goes down, without worrying about debits or credits yet.\n\n**Before Lesson 3:** Make sure you can explain the gray zone accounts without looking at your notes. The dual-impact concept in Lesson 3 builds directly on today's classification skill."
            }
          }
        ]
